Lung function and walking distance for patients with COPD

This analysis is part of //… in Coursera.

Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary disease (COPD) includes chronic bronchitis and empythsema and is caused by exposure to irritantes.

Lung functions tests check how well the lungs work. We are going to analyze the relationship between the lung function (FEV1) and predictors.

Data

The dataset contains data on 101 patients and 24 variables such as age, gender, smoker, diabetes, hypertension and two measurments on walking distance (in meters).

The forced vital capacity (FVC) is a test of the total amount of air exhaled during the FEV test (Function lung). It ranges from 1.14 to 5.37 and its mean is 2.955. The histogram suggest that the distribution is not normal, this is confirmed by the Shapiro Normality test.

summary(COPD$FVC)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   1.140   2.270   2.770   2.955   3.630   5.370
# Histogram

  geom_histogram(bins = 10, fill = 'darkblue', alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_vline(data = COPD, aes(xintercept = mean(FVC)), 
             color = 'grey', 
             linetype = 'dashed') +
  theme_tufte()

# Normality test
shapiro.test(COPD$FVC)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  COPD$FVC
## W = 0.96294, p-value = 0.006197

Shapiro Normality results in a W-statistic of 0.96294 and p-value of 0.006197. We reject the null hypothesis of normal distibution as p-value < 0.05.

Predictors

The histograms of all the predictors show that distributions of MWT1, MWT2 and MWTBest are very similar. This is expected as MWT1 and MWT2 are walking meters by the patient and MWTBest indicates the best of both measurements. The distribution of age show that there are mainly old adults in the sample and gender is not equally distributed.

Multiple Linear Regression

First we will run simple regressions between the outcome (MWT1Best) against forced vital capacity(FVC) and age to compare results from simple regression with multiple regression.

In the simple model with age as predictor, it is statistically significant but the model fits the data poorly (Adj R-squared is 0.04). The other simple model fits the data better but still poorly (Adj. R Squared is 0.19). FVC is statistically significant and its coefficient ranges between 29.05 to 68.21.

# Linear regressions
lr_age <- lm(MWT1Best ~ AGE, data = COPD)
lr_fvc <- lm(MWT1Best ~ FVC , data = COPD)
table <- sjPlot::tab_model(lr_age,lr_fvc,
                  dv.labels = c('Linear regression - Age', 'Linear Regression - FVC'),
                  p.style = 'a')
table
  Linear regression - Age Linear Regression - FVC
Predictors Estimates CI Estimates CI
(Intercept) 616.45 *** 431.02 – 801.88 254.95 *** 193.87 – 316.03
AGE -3.10 * -5.74 – -0.47
FVC 48.63 *** 29.05 – 68.21
Observations 100 100
R2 / R2 adjusted 0.053 / 0.043 0.199 / 0.190
  • p<0.05   ** p<0.01   *** p<0.001

The multiple linear regression fits the data better than the two simple models (Adj. R square is 0.21), this means that the multivariate model explians 21% of the variance in the data. This R2 is marginally higher in this model compared with simple models. Now the age is no longer significant and ranges for FVC coefficient is smaller(26.55 to 65.56).

# Multiple Linear
mlr <- lm(MWT1Best ~ AGE + FVC, data = COPD)

Checking assumptions

Collinearity

To check if there is collinearity between FVC and AGE we are going to plot the scatter plots and decide wether we need a Pearson correlation test or Spearman correlation test.

ggplot(COPD, aes(x = FVC, y = AGE)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_tufte()

# Correlation tests
cor.test(COPD$FVC,COPD$AGE, use = 'complete.obs', method = 'pearson')
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  COPD$FVC and COPD$AGE
## t = -1.4605, df = 99, p-value = 0.1473
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.33126283  0.05168036
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## -0.1452257
cor.test(COPD$FVC,COPD$AGE, use = 'complete.obs', method = 'spearman')
## Warning in cor.test.default(COPD$FVC, COPD$AGE, use = "complete.obs",
## method = "spearman"): Cannot compute exact p-value with ties
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  COPD$FVC and COPD$AGE
## S = 202110, p-value = 0.07642
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##        rho 
## -0.1771108

Correlation between variables is -0.14 (Pearson) and -0.17(Spearman). P-value in both cases is > 0.05, the null hypothesis of not association between variables cannot be rejected so we conclude that there is no enough evidence for association between age and FVC and thus the no collinearity assumption is met.

# Check model assumptions
#par(mfrow=c(2,2)) 
plot(mlr)

The heteroscedasticty assumption is reasonable as the residuals vs fitted plot shows a constant variance. The QQ plot shows that most of the point lie on the line for perfect normal distribution of the residual. Thus the residual normal distribution is met. The Cook’s plot show that there were two values with high impact on the regression(observations 100 and 9).

VIF: Variance inflation factor

It is useful when we need to measure the association across more than two variables. As spearman and pearsons correlation test only accounts for pairwise relationships.

  • VIF = 1: No collinearity
  • VIF > 4: Further investigation
  • VIF > 10: Collinearity

Binary variables

The binary variables should be coded as 0 and 1. 0 will be the reference category. - Female = 0 - Male = 1

The simple regression model of walking distance against gender shows that the estimated coefficient is 30.51. This means that the average walking distance that men can walk is 30% larger than the distance that woman can walk.

The intercept (379) is the average walking distance for female.

Categorical variables

One of the categories is choosen as the reference. COPD severity takes different values: ‘mild’,‘moderate’,‘severe’ and ‘very severe’.

‘Mild’ is the rerefence category and the coefficients of the other categories should be intepreted related to the reference. The regression coefficients show how much walking distance changes for moderate, severe and very severe compared to mild.

All the coefficients are negative, this suggest that the walking distance increases as COPD severity increases.

Feature engineering

A comorbid feature will be created to consider if the patient suffered at least from one of the comorbidities in the dataset: diabetes, muscular, hypertension, atrialfib and IHD.

# List categorical variables
categorical <- c('Diabetes','muscular','hypertension','AtrialFib','IHD')

# Check data types
#str(COPD[,categorical])

# Transform to factors
#COPD[,categorical] <- data.frame(apply(COPD[categorical],2,as.factor))

# Check data types
#str(COPD[,categorical])

# Create comorbid
COPD <- COPD %>% mutate(comorbid = ifelse(Diabetes + 
                                          muscular +
                                          hypertension + 
                                          AtrialFib + 
                                          IHD > 0, 1,0))
# Transform fo factor
COPD$comorbid <- factor(COPD$comorbid)

# Simple models
features <- c('AGE','FEV1','gender','COPDSEVERITY')

# Function to develop models
linear_model <- function(feature) {
  # capture strings and create variable
  name <- paste0('sm_',feature)
  form = lm ~ feature
  model <- lm(MWT1Best ~ COPD[[feature]], data = COPD)
  assign(name, model, envir = .GlobalEnv)
}

# Iterate features
for (feature in features){
  linear_model(feature)
}

Interactions between variables - binary

Interactions ocurr when the predictor variables has a different effec on the outcome depending on the value of another explanatory variable. - Diabetic: 0 if not, 1 otherwise - AtrialFib (atrial fibrillation): 0 if not , 1 otherwise

The interaction between diabetes and atrialfib is statistically significant. A patient with nor diabetes or atrialfib walks an average of 428 meters. If a patient only has diabetes, the average meters they walk is 380. For patients with Atrialfib(and no diabetes) the mean walking distance is 327 meters. A patient with both conditions walks an average of 218 meters.

# Data type: Integer
COPD$Diabetes <- as.integer(COPD$Diabetes)
COPD$AtrialFib <- as.integer(COPD$AtrialFib)

Model development

Model that understand all the variables in the outcome (causes).

Question: What improves SGRQ (life quality) in patients with COPD?

We cannot add all the variables with small dataset as it can causes overfitting.

Variable selection

Assumption of independance. If there is collinearity the first variable will have impact but the second won’t.

  • Forward selection: Adds variables one at the time and keep them if they are statistically significant.
  • Backward selection: Starts with all the variables and remove one by one by level of significance.
  • Stepwise: Equals forward selection but testing if the overall performance of the model is increased. The variables that do not met a threshold of significance are dropped: the problem is that it depende on the dataset and it introduces bias.

Problems with automated approaches

  • They yield R-squared values that are badly biased to be high.
  • The F and chi-squared tests quoted next to each variable on the printout do not have the claimed distribution.
  • They yield confidence intervals for effects and predicted values that are falsely narrow; see Altman and Andersen (1989).
  • They yield p-values that do not have the proper meaning, and the proper correction for them is a difficult problem.
  • They give biased regression coefficients that need shrinkage (the coefficients for remaining variables are too large); see Tibshirani (1996).
  • They have severe problems in the presence of collinearity.
  • They are based on methods (e.g., F tests for nested models) that were intended to be used to test prespecified hypotheses.
  • Increasing the sample size does not help very much; see Derksen and Keselman (1992).
  • They allow us to not think about the problem.

To select variables: - Check literature, previous studies. - Exclude variable if it has too many missings - Narrow distributions: Variables with low variability do not provide info - Collinearity: If yoy have two correlated variables, choose one.

Feature engineering: Variables can be aggregated to make a new one

Data reduction methods are useful to have less variables in the model.

Data dedging:

What to avoid Do not drop variables using the 5% significance level Backward selection is the least offensive of the automatic variable selection (do not use stepwise or forward selection) Known predictors (by the literature) should be included, regardless of the 5% confidence level. They affect the other variable’s coefficients.

Optimal number of predictors: n/10 or n/20. Where n is the total sample size.
